law.text:
Article 1.<W 1996-07-15/33, art. 3, 012; Entry into force: 22-10-1996> [5 para. 1.]5 For the purposes of this law, the following definitions apply:
 (1) foreigner: anyone who does not provide proof that they possess Belgian nationality;
 (2) the Minister: the Minister competent for access to the territory, residence, establishment, and removal of foreigners;
 [1 (3) national of a third country: anyone who is not a citizen of the Union and who is not a person covered by Community law regarding free movement, as defined in Article 2, point 5, of the Schengen Borders Code;
 (4) illegal stay: presence on the territory of a foreigner who does not or no longer meets the conditions for access to or residence on the territory;
 (5) return: the fact that a national of a third country, either voluntarily after having been subject to a removal decision or forcibly, returns to their country of origin or a transit country pursuant to Community or bilateral readmission agreements, or to another third country to which the person concerned decides to return voluntarily and where they are authorized or admitted to stay;
 (6) removal decision: the decision establishing the illegality of a foreigner's stay and imposing an obligation to return;
 (7) removal: the enforcement of the removal decision, namely the physical removal from the territory;
 (8) [4 entry ban: the decision that may accompany a removal decision prohibiting access to and residence on the territory of the Kingdom or the territory of all Member States, including the territory of the Kingdom, for a specified period;]4
 (9) voluntary departure: leaving the territory within the period set for this in the removal decision;
 (10) voluntary return: the return of a person to their country of origin or a third country where they are admitted to stay on the territory, following an independently taken decision to use a return assistance program developed by the host country's government;
 (11) [5 risk of absconding: the fact that there are reasons to believe that a foreigner subject to a removal procedure, a procedure for granting international protection, or a procedure to determine or transfer to the Member State responsible for handling the request for international protection, in view of the criteria listed in para. 2, will abscond.]5
 (12) vulnerable person: both accompanied and unaccompanied minors, persons with disabilities, elderly persons, pregnant women, single parents with minor children, and persons who have been tortured or raped or have suffered other serious forms of psychological, physical, or sexual violence;
 (13) Decision 2004/573/EC: the Council Decision of 29 April 2004 concerning the organization of joint removal flights of nationals of third countries against whom individual removal measures have been taken from the territory of two or more Member States;
 (14) identified foreigner: any foreigner
 - who possesses a valid travel document, a valid passport, or a valid identity document, or
 - who has been recognized as a national by the national authority of their country, which has declared itself willing to issue a laissez-passer, or
 - who falls under the category of nationalities for which the Minister can issue a laissez-passer themselves;]1
 [2 (15) [7 ...]7]2
 [3 (16) international protection: refugee status and subsidiary protection status;
 (17) [6 SIS: the Schengen Information System as referred to in [10 ...]10 Regulation (EU) No 2018/1860 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 28 November 2018 concerning the use of the Schengen Information System for the return of illegally staying third-country nationals and Regulation (EU) No 2018/1861 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 28 November 2018 establishing, operating, and using the Schengen Information System (SIS) for border control purposes, amending the Convention implementing the Schengen Agreement, and repealing Regulation (EC) No 1987/2006;]6]3
 [4 (18) General National Database: the police database referred to in Article 44/7 of the Act of 5 August 1992 on the Police Service;]4
 [5 (19) final decision in the context of an request for international protection: a decision on whether the foreigner is granted refugee status or subsidiary protection status and against which no appeal is possible under Title Ibis, regardless of whether this appeal allows the applicant to remain on the territory pending the outcome;
 (20) subsequent request for international protection: any later request for international protection made after a final decision has been taken on a previous request, including decisions taken on the basis of Article 57/6/5, para. 1, (1), (2), (3), (4), (5), (7), and (8);]5
 [7 (21) "airport transit visa": the visa required under the Visa Code for transit through the international transit zones of airports on the territory and issued pursuant to that Code;
 (22) "short stay visa": the visa required, under Regulation (EU) 2018/1806 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 14 November 2018 establishing the list of third countries whose nationals must be in possession of a visa when crossing the external borders and the list of third countries whose nationals are exempt from that requirement, for staying or transiting within the territory for a maximum duration of ninety days and issued pursuant to the Visa Code;
 (23) "long stay visa": the visa required pursuant to Article 18 of the Schengen Agreement for stays exceeding ninety days on the territory and which enables its holder to demonstrate that he or she was authorized or admitted to stay for more than ninety days in accordance with applicable legal and regulatory provisions;
 (24) "Visa Code": Regulation (EC) No 810/2009 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 13 July 2009 establishing a Community Code on Visas (Visa Code);
 (25) "Schengen Borders Code": Regulation (EU) 2016/399 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 9 March 2016 on a Union Code on the crossing of borders by persons (Schengen Borders Code);
 (26) "Schengen Agreement": agreement implementing the accord signed on 14 June 1985 at Schengen between the governments of the states of the Benelux Economic Union, the Federal Republic of Germany, and the French Republic concerning the gradual abolition of checks at their common borders;]7
 [8 (27) cooperation agreement of 2 February 2018: the cooperation agreement of 2 February 2018 between the Federal State, the Walloon Region, the Flemish Region, the Brussels-Capital Region, and the German-speaking Community regarding coordination between the policy on work permits and the policy on residence permits and standards concerning the employment and residence of foreign workers;
 (28) cooperation agreement of 6 December 2018: the cooperation agreement of 6 December 2018 between the Federal State, the Walloon Region, the Flemish Region, the Brussels-Capital Region, and the German-speaking Community implementing the cooperation agreement of 2 February 2018 between the Federal State, the Walloon Region, the Flemish Region, the Brussels-Capital Region, and the German-speaking Community regarding coordination between the policy on work permits and the policy on residence permits and standards concerning the employment and residence of foreign workers;
 (29) competent regional authority: the regional or community authority which, pursuant to regional or community decrees, regulations, and decisions, is competent for the employment of foreign workers;]8
 [9 (30) the withdrawal agreement: the Agreement on the Withdrawal of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland from the European Union and the European Atomic Energy Community (2019/C 384 I/01);
 (31) beneficiary of the withdrawal agreement: the person referred to in Article 10 of the withdrawal agreement]9;
 [12 (32) EES: the Entry/Exit System as referred to in Regulation (EU) 2017/2226 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 30 November 2017 establishing an Entry/Exit System (EES) for registering entry and exit data and refusal of entry data regarding third-country nationals crossing the external borders and establishing conditions for access to the EES for law enforcement purposes and amending the Convention Implementing the Schengen Agreement and Regulations (EC) No 767/2008 and (EU) No 1077/2011 (hereinafter: Regulation (EU) 2017/2226)]12;
 [11 (33) closed center: the place referred to in Article 74/8, paras. 1 and 2, managed by the Immigration Office and intended for the reception of foreigners subject to an administrative detention measure;
 (34) residential unit: the place referred to in Article 74/8, paras. 1 and 2, managed by the Immigration Office, adapted to the needs of families with minor children, which may be left under conditions determined by the King, and intended for the reception of families with minor children subject to an administrative detention measure.]11
 [5 para. 2. The risk of absconding referred to in paragraph 1, (11), must be current and real. It is established after an individual investigation and based on one or more of the following objective criteria, taking into account all circumstances specific to each case:
 (1) the person concerned has not submitted a residence application after illegal entry or during illegal stay, or has not submitted their request for international protection within the time limit provided by this law;
 (2) the person concerned has used false or misleading information or false or falsified documents, or has committed fraud or other unlawful means in the context of a procedure for international protection, stay, removal, or pushback;
 (3) the person concerned does not or has not cooperated in relation to authorities responsible for the implementation of and/or supervision of compliance with regulations on access to the territory, residence, establishment, and removal of foreigners;
 (4) the person concerned has made clear that they do not wish to comply with one of the following measures or has already failed to comply with one of these measures:
 a) a transfer, pushback, or removal measure;
 b) an entry ban that has neither been lifted nor suspended;
 c) a less coercive measure than a deprivation of liberty measure aimed at guaranteeing their transfer, pushback, or removal, whether it is a restrictive measure or other measure;
 d) a restrictive measure aimed at guaranteeing public order or national security;
 e) a measure taken by another Member State equivalent to the measures referred to in a), b), c), or d);
 (5) the person concerned is subject to an entry ban in the Kingdom and/or in another Member State that has neither been lifted nor suspended;
 (6) the person concerned has immediately after being subject to a decision refusing entry or residence or a decision ending their stay, or immediately after being subject to a pushback or removal measure, submitted a new residence application or new request for international protection;
 (7) while being questioned on this point, the person concerned has concealed that they have already provided fingerprints in another State bound by European regulations concerning the determination of the Member State responsible for examining an application for international protection, after having submitted a request for international protection;
 (8) the person concerned has submitted multiple requests for international protection and/or residence applications in the Kingdom or one or more other Member States which have resulted in a negative decision or have not led to the issuance of a residence permit;
 (9) while being questioned on this point, the person concerned has concealed that they previously submitted a request for international protection in another State bound by European regulations concerning the determination of the State responsible for the examination of an international protection request;
 (10) the person concerned has declared or their file shows that they came to the Kingdom for purposes other than those for which they submitted a request for international protection or residence application;
 (11) the person concerned is subject to a fine for having submitted a manifestly unfounded appeal to the Immigration Appeals Board.]5

